        <exercise><title>Inverse and row operations, lower triangular matrix</title>
            <!-- <introduction>
                <p>
                    Complete the following problems by hand, without using Sage or another matrix calculator.
                </p>
            </introduction> -->
            <task workspace="1in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use row reducing to calculate the inverse of the matrix below. Be sure to write down which row operations you did.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>
                            C=\left[\begin{array}{rrr}2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp -3 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 1  \end{array}\right]
                        </m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            C^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{rrr}\frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp \frac{1}{3} \amp 1  \end{array}\right]
                        </me>,
                        which was accomplished by performing the row operations
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \frac{1}{2}R_1\amp \rightarrow R_1</mrow>
                            <mrow> -3R_1+R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                            <mrow> 2R_1+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                            <mrow> -\frac{1}{3}R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                            <mrow> -R_2+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                        </md>.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1in">
                <statement>
                    <!-- <p>
                        Augment the matrix below by the identity matrix.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>
                            D=\left[\begin{array}{rrr}\frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 1 \end{array}\right]
                        </m>   
                    </p> -->
                        <!-- <me>
                            D=\left[\begin{array}{rrr}\frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 1 \end{array}\right]
                        </me>. -->
                    <p>
                        Even though this is not our usual Gauss-Jordan algorithm, perform the following row operations
                         in order on the matrix <m>D</m>. What does the result tell you about <m>D^{-1}</m>?  What do you notice 
                         about the row operations compared to the row operations done on <m>C</m>?
                    </p>
                    <sidebyside widths="25% 70%">
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> R_2+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                                <mrow> -3R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                                <mrow> -2R_1+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                                <mrow> 3R_1+R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                                <mrow> 2R_1\amp \rightarrow R_1</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>
                        D=\left[\begin{array}{rrr|rrr}\frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\ \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 1\amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\end{array}\right]
                    </m>
                        </p>
                    </sidebyside>
                        

                        <!-- <md>
                            <mrow> R_2+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                            <mrow> -3R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                            <mrow> -2R_1+R_3\amp \rightarrow R_3</mrow>
                            <mrow> 3R_1+R_2\amp \rightarrow R_2</mrow>
                            <mrow> 2R_1\amp \rightarrow R_1</mrow>
                        </md>. -->
                        
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            D^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{2}{3} \end{array}\right]
                        </me>,
                       and <m>D=C^{-1}</m>, <m>D^{-1}=C</m>.  The inverse of <m>C^{-1}</m> is <m>C</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The row operations are the inverse operations, done in reverse order.  The inverse of scaling is scaling by the reciprocal.
                        The inverse of <q>multiply Row 1 by <m>k</m> and add to Row 2</q> is <q>multiply Row 1 by <m>-k</m> and add</q> to Row 2.
                        Prompt students to think about the inverse of swapping two rows (perform the same swap again to swap them back).
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </task>
