    <page>
        <exercise><title>Investigating properties of the inverse</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    For this problem, use Sage or another matrix inverse calculator. 
                    Note that once you've defined the matrix <m>A</m> in Sage, Sage can find the inverse without needing to augment and row reduce
                    using <c>A.inverse()</c> or <c>A^-1</c>.
                </p>
                <sage>
                    <input>
                        A=matrix(QQ,3,3,[[1,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,1]])
                        show(A)
                    </input>
                </sage>
                <p>
                    Consider the square matrices
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A = \begin{bmatrix}
                        1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
                        2 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
                        1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
                        \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp
                        B = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
                        1 \amp -2 \amp -1 \\
                        -1 \amp 5 \amp 6 \\
                        5 \amp -4 \amp 6 \\
                        \end{array}\right]</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <!-- <sidebyside widths="30% 30%" margins="0% 30%">
                <p>
                    <m>A=\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{2}{3} \end{array}\right]</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>B=\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}\frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -\frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{3}{2} \end{array}\right]</m>
                </p>
            </sidebyside> -->
            </introduction>
            <task workspace="1in">
                <p>
                    Calculate <m>A^{-1}</m> and <m>B^{-1}</m>.
                </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace=".5in">
                <p>
                    Show that <m>AB</m> is invertible by finding a matrix <m>X</m>
                    such that <m>(AB)X=I</m>. 
                </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1in">
                <p>
                    Use Sage to calculate <m>AB</m>, <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>, <m>A^{-1}B^{-1}</m>, and <m>B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>. What do you notice?
                </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Consider the product
                        <me>
                        (EF)(E^{-1}F^{-1})
                        </me>
                        and use associativity to regroup the products so
                        that the middle two terms are multiplied first.
                        Do the same for 
                        <me>
                        (F^{-1}E^{-1})(EF)
                        </me>.
                        What do you get?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task workspace=".5in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        What is the inverse of <m>B^2</m> in terms of <m>B^{-1}</m>?  What about the inverse of <m>B^5</m>? Use Sage to verify your conjectures.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task workspace=".5in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Calculate <m>A+B</m>, <m>(A+B)^{-1}</m> and <m>A^{-1}+B^{-1}</m>. What do you observe?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exercise>

